        <% } %>
      </div>
      <div style="margin-bottom:48px"><a href="/blog" style="font-size:.9rem;font-weight:700;color:#16a34a;text-decoration:none;display:inline-flex;align-items:center;gap:6px;">View All Posts &#8594;</a></div>

      <div style="border-top:1px solid #e5e7eb;padding-top:48px;margin-top:0">
        <div class="section-title-wrap">
          <span class="section-eyebrow">How These Calculators Work</span>
          <h2>Understanding Your Federal Tax Estimate</h2>
        </div>
        <div class="how-it-works-grid">
          <div>
            <p style="font-size:.95rem;color:#4b5563;line-height:1.7;margin:0 0 16px">
              Every calculator on MyTaxCalcs uses the same formulas the IRS publishes in its official
              instructions. Start with your gross income, subtract your standard or itemized deduction
              to arrive at taxable income, then apply the 2025 tax brackets progressively -- not as a
              flat rate. The result is your estimated federal tax liability before any credits or
              withholding adjustments.
            </p>
            <p style="font-size:.95rem;color:#4b5563;line-height:1.7;margin:0 0 16px">
              Tax brackets are marginal, which means only the income inside each bracket is taxed at
              that rate. A single filer with $80,000 of taxable income does not pay 22% on all $80,000 --
              they pay 10% on the first $11,925, 12% on income up to $48,475, and 22% only on the
              remaining amount above that threshold.
            </p>
            <p style="font-size:.95rem;color:#4b5563;line-height:1.7;margin:0">
              Results are estimates. They do not account for every individual credit, the Alternative
              Minimum Tax, passive income rules, or state-level variations. Use them as a planning
              baseline -- not as a substitute for a CPA, enrolled agent, or tax software.
            </p>
          </div>
          <div>
            <div style="background:#f9fafb;border:1px solid #e5e7eb;border-radius:16px;padding:24px">
              <h3 style="font-size:1rem;font-weight:700;color:#111827;margin:0 0 16px">2025 standard deductions (IRS Rev. Proc. 2024-40)</h3>
              <table style="width:100%;font-size:.88rem;border-collapse:collapse">
                <tr style="border-bottom:1px solid #e5e7eb">
                  <td style="padding:9px 0;color:#374151;font-weight:600">Single</td>
                  <td style="padding:9px 0;text-align:right;color:#111827;font-weight:700">$15,000</td>
                </tr>
                <tr style="border-bottom:1px solid #e5e7eb">
                  <td style="padding:9px 0;color:#374151;font-weight:600">Married filing jointly</td>
                  <td style="padding:9px 0;text-align:right;color:#111827;font-weight:700">$30,000</td>
                </tr>
                <tr style="border-bottom:1px solid #e5e7eb">
                  <td style="padding:9px 0;color:#374151;font-weight:600">Head of household</td>
                  <td style="padding:9px 0;text-align:right;color:#111827;font-weight:700">$22,500</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                  <td style="padding:9px 0;color:#374151;font-weight:600">Married filing separately</td>
                  <td style="padding:9px 0;text-align:right;color:#111827;font-weight:700">$15,000</td>
                </tr>
              </table>
              <a href="/standard-deduction-2025" style="font-size:.82rem;font-weight:700;color:#16a34a;text-decoration:none;display:inline-flex;align-items:center;gap:4px;margin-top:14px">Full standard deduction guide &#8594;</a>
            </div>
            <div style="background:#f0fdf4;border:1px solid #d1fae5;border-radius:16px;padding:20px;margin-top:16px">
